    en: {"title":"How to speed up request processing","description":"Requests sit in a shared inbox and get handled in order — customers wait for hours. How to build routing and a fast first response without losing quality.","h1":"How to speed up request processing","sections":[{"title":"Short answer","paragraphs":["Request processing speed depends less on headcount in support and more on where a request lands in the first second: a shared inbox, or straight into the CRM with routing by type and priority.", "An AI agent qualifies the request up front, pulls the customer's context, and either resolves a routine question itself or hands it to a human with a ready summary."]},{"title":"What usually breaks","paragraphs":["Requests from different channels — website, email, messengers — land in one shared queue with no prioritization, so urgent requests wait alongside routine ones.", "Companies add a chatbot on top of routing chaos — it replies fast, but hands requests to humans without context, so total processing time doesn't actually drop."]},{"title":"4-week plan","paragraphs":["Week 1 — audit request channels and current response time. Weeks 2–3 — CRM routing and an AI agent for first-pass qualification. Week 4 — measure average first-response time and decide on the SLA."]},{"title":"How Bober AI Systems helps","paragraphs":["We build a system that recognizes the request, finds the relevant data, and either answers it directly or routes it to the right specialist — no manual inbox sorting.", "Time savings on routine operations run 40–80%, with payback from 3 months — calculated during the audit, before development starts."]}],"faq":[{"q":"How much can request processing time actually drop?","a":"It depends on the current process, but routing plus AI qualification at the front door usually cuts first-response time 2–4x by removing the shared-inbox queue."},{"q":"Does automation replace support staff?","a":"No — it removes routine, repetitive requests, while complex and sensitive cases still go to a person, who now gets them with ready context."}]},
